    differentiationNotes: `Struggling learners benefit from explaining why chair seats are at a specific height (so feet can rest flat on the floor, keeping knees at a comfortable angle) and calculating the area of a rectangular tabletop using multiplication, such as a table one hundred twenty centimeters long and eighty centimeters wide having an area of nine thousand six hundred square centimeters. Advanced learners benefit from analyzing how ergonomic principles guide furniture design for different purposes, explaining how seat height, desk height, and lumbar support all relate to human body dimensions \u2014 and writing a multi-paragraph report comparing joinery techniques explaining why mortise-and-tenon joints are stronger than nails because the large surface area inside the mortise creates a powerful glue bond and the interlocking shape resists pulling forces, with engineering reasoning and historical examples.`,
    parentTakeaway: `Furniture as design engineering \u2014 examine furniture together discussing why chairs have specific seat heights (so feet rest flat on the floor with knees at ninety degrees), why desks are at particular levels (so forearms are parallel to the floor while writing), and how drawers use slides and runners; measure furniture dimensions and calculate areas and volumes using multiplication, such as calculating shelf storage space; discuss different wood types like oak being harder and more durable than pine, and why harder woods last longer for heavily used furniture; observe joinery in furniture discussing how pieces connect without visible nails, looking for dovetail joints in drawers and mortise-and-tenon joints in chairs and tables.`,
